                <head>107. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>In a July 20, 1961, memorandum to President <persName corresp="#p_KJF1"
                        >Kennedy</persName>, Robert Komer of the National Security Council Staff
                    recommended “stepping up the momentum in South Vietnam. I believe it very
                    important that this government have a major anti-Communist victory to its credit
                    in the six months before the Berlin crisis is likely to get really hot. Few
                    things would be better calculated to show Moscow and Peiping that we mean
                    business than an obvious (if not yet definitive) turnaround in Vietnam.” For
                    text, see <ref target="frus1961-63v01#pg_234">
                        <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1961–1963, volume I, pages
                        234</ref>–<ref target="frus1961-63v01#pg_236">236</ref>.</p>
            </div>
        </body>
